SIMPLE: shiver
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shiver
<hw>Shiv"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>schivere</ets>, fr. <ets>shive</ets>; cf. G. <ets>schifer</ets> a
splinter, slate, OHG. <ets>scivere</ets> a splinter, Dan. & Sw.
<ets>skifer</ets> a slate. See <er>Shive</er>, and cf.
<er>Skever</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the small pieces, or
splinters, into which a brittle thing is broken by sudden violence; --
generally used in the plural.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧All to <xex>shivers</xex>
dashed.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A thin slice; a shive.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov.
Eng.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>shiver</xex> of their own loaf.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of your soft bread, not but a <qex>shiver</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A variety of blue
slate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A sheave or small wheel in a
pulley.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A small wedge, as for fastening the bolt of a window
shutter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A spindle.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shiver</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shiver
<hw>Shiv"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shivered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shivering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>schiveren</ets>,
<ets>scheveren</ets>; cf. OD. <ets>scheveren</ets>. See <er>Shiver</er>
a fragment.]</ety> <def>To break into many small pieces, or splinters;
to shatter; to dash to pieces by a blow; <as>as, to <ex>shiver</ex> a
glass goblet</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the ground⟦br⟧
With <qex>shivered</qex> armor strown.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shiver</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shiver
<hw>Shiv"er</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To separate suddenly into many
small pieces or parts; to be shattered.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There <qex>shiver</qex> shafts upon shields thick.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The natural world, should gravity once cease, . . . would
instantly <qex>shiver</qex> into millions of atoms.</q>
<rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shiver</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Shiver
<hw>Shiv"er</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>chiveren</ets>,
<ets>cheveren</ets>; of uncertain origin. This word seems to have been
confused with <ets>shiver</ets> to shatter.]</ety> <def>To tremble; to
vibrate; to quiver; to shake, as from cold or fear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Prometheus is laid⟦br⟧
On icy Caucasus to <qex>shiver</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The man that <qex>shivered</qex> on the brink of sin,⟦br⟧
Thus steeled and hardened, ventures boldly in.</q>
<rj><qau>Creech.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shiver</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Shiver
<hw>Shiv"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To cause to
shake or tremble, as a sail, by steering close to the wind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shiver</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Shiver
<hw>Shiv"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of shivering or
trembling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shiveringly</ent>⟦br⟧
